WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:05.600
Muhammad Ali, by Bernard Smith, Level 1.

00:05.600 --> 00:08.760
Who is Muhammad Ali?

00:08.760 --> 00:11.760
Why is he famous?

00:11.760 --> 00:20.480
Why did he have two names, Cassius Clay, in his early years, and later Muhammad Ali?

00:20.480 --> 00:24.000
And what is he doing now?

00:24.000 --> 00:31.440
Muhammad Ali was, of course, a famous boxer, a world champion.

00:31.440 --> 00:35.360
But he fought for black Americans too.

00:35.360 --> 00:41.360
He stopped boxing in 1981 because he was sick.

00:41.360 --> 00:47.080
But today, he is fighting for peace in the world.

00:47.080 --> 00:51.120
The Red and White Bike

00:51.120 --> 00:56.240
The story starts with a boy's new red and white bike.

00:56.240 --> 00:59.640
It is 1954.

00:59.640 --> 01:03.880
Joe Martin is a policeman in Louisville, Kentucky.

01:03.880 --> 01:08.800
But he teaches boxing in a gym in the evenings too.

01:08.800 --> 01:13.320
One day, two young black boys come into the gym.

01:13.320 --> 01:15.680
One of them sees Joe.

01:16.240 --> 01:19.680
Excuse me, he says.

01:19.680 --> 01:23.680
Are you Joe Martin, the policeman?

01:23.680 --> 01:26.800
That's right, Joe says.

01:26.800 --> 01:29.200
What's your problem?

01:29.200 --> 01:32.960
It's my new back, the boy says.

01:32.960 --> 01:35.400
It's red and white.

01:35.400 --> 01:40.840
He was in front of this building, and now it's not there.

01:40.840 --> 01:46.000
The young boy is unhappy and very angry.

01:46.000 --> 01:49.520
I'm going to find the boy with my back.

01:49.520 --> 01:53.080
Then I'm going to whoop him.

01:53.080 --> 01:56.880
He says again and again.

01:56.880 --> 01:59.160
Joe Martin smiles.

01:59.160 --> 02:02.160
The boy is about 12 years old.

02:02.160 --> 02:07.360
He is tall with long legs, and he is thin.

02:07.360 --> 02:09.360
Can you box?

02:09.360 --> 02:11.480
Joe asks.

02:11.480 --> 02:15.920
No, I can't box, the boy says.

02:15.920 --> 02:19.280
But I want to whoop that boy.

02:19.280 --> 02:22.320
Joe smiles again.

02:22.320 --> 02:25.040
Come here to the gym first.

02:25.040 --> 02:28.240
Maybe I can teach you.

02:28.240 --> 02:31.800
OK, the boy says.

02:31.800 --> 02:34.160
I'd like that.

02:34.160 --> 02:37.440
Good, Joe says.

02:37.440 --> 02:40.000
What's your name?

02:40.000 --> 02:43.280
Cassius, the boy says.

02:43.280 --> 02:46.560
Cassius Clay.

02:46.560 --> 02:50.320
Joe doesn't know it, but in only 10 years,

02:50.320 --> 02:54.320
that young black boy is going to be a world boxing champion.

02:57.240 --> 03:01.040
After that, Cassius went to Joe Martin's gym

03:01.040 --> 03:03.640
six days a week.

03:03.640 --> 03:07.520
He was strong and quick on his feet,

03:07.520 --> 03:12.240
and he started boxing with the other boys in the gym.

03:12.240 --> 03:15.800
He didn't box for money, of course.

03:15.800 --> 03:19.640
He boxed because he liked it.

03:19.640 --> 03:22.640
He usually won his fights.

03:22.640 --> 03:29.680
He was good, but he wasn't a good student at school.

03:29.680 --> 03:32.800
He had a lot of problems.

03:32.800 --> 03:36.800
He was a good boy from a good family.

03:36.800 --> 03:41.080
He was friendly, and his teachers liked him.

03:41.080 --> 03:45.680
But school work was very difficult for him.

03:45.680 --> 03:50.560
The only important thing in the world for him, then, was boxing.

03:53.520 --> 04:01.800
In six years, he had 108 fights, and he won 100 of them.

04:01.800 --> 04:08.800
Then, in 1960, he went to Rome and boxed for the United States.

04:12.800 --> 04:16.800
The Olympic Games.

04:16.800 --> 04:22.800
In 1960, Cassius was only 18 years old.

04:22.800 --> 04:26.800
He was in Rome for the Olympic Games.

04:26.800 --> 04:33.800
He beat every opponent, and he won an Olympic medal for the United States.

04:33.800 --> 04:37.800
He was an Olympic boxing champion,

04:37.800 --> 04:44.800
and he didn't take off his Olympic medal for weeks, night or day.

04:44.800 --> 04:49.800
At home in Louisville, he was famous.

04:49.800 --> 04:55.800
But he was black, and in Louisville in the 1960s,

04:55.800 --> 05:01.800
there were places for white people and places for black people.

05:01.800 --> 05:07.800
In many hotels, theaters, stores, and buses,

05:07.800 --> 05:12.800
black people didn't sit with white people.

05:12.800 --> 05:18.800
One day, Cassius wanted to buy a drink in a white store.

05:18.800 --> 05:21.800
It was a problem.

05:21.800 --> 05:25.800
Whites only, they said.

05:25.800 --> 05:28.800
But I'm the Olympic boxing champion.

05:28.800 --> 05:33.800
I'm famous, Cassius said.

05:33.800 --> 05:36.800
Whites only, they answered.

05:36.800 --> 05:39.800
Go away!

05:39.800 --> 05:43.800
Cassius was very unhappy about that.

05:43.800 --> 05:48.800
I'm going to be the world champion, he said.

05:48.800 --> 05:51.800
I'm going to be important,

05:51.800 --> 05:58.800
then white people are going to sit down with me and listen to me.

05:58.800 --> 06:04.800
After the Olympic Games, Cassius started to fight for money.

06:04.800 --> 06:08.800
Boxing wasn't a game now.

06:08.800 --> 06:11.800
It was his work.

06:11.800 --> 06:14.800
He moved from Louisville to Miami.

06:14.800 --> 06:20.800
He went to a new gym in Miami and he had new friends.

06:20.800 --> 06:24.800
One of them was Angelo Dundee.

06:24.800 --> 06:34.800
He worked with Cassius in the gym and was always with him for his fights.

06:34.800 --> 06:40.800
The first fight with Sonny Liston.

06:40.800 --> 06:46.800
In 1964, Cassius Clay was 22 years old.

06:46.800 --> 06:50.800
He was tall and strong.

06:50.800 --> 07:00.800
After 19 fights and 19 wins, he wanted to fight the world champion, Sonny Liston.

07:00.800 --> 07:05.800
Clay always moved very quickly in his fights.

07:05.800 --> 07:10.800
He danced here and there in the ring.

07:10.800 --> 07:14.800
His opponents were big, strong men.

07:14.800 --> 07:22.800
But they lost because their punches usually didn't hit him.

07:22.800 --> 07:29.800
But Liston was the world champion and a very strong boxer.

07:29.800 --> 07:32.800
The newspapers in the U.S. said,

07:32.800 --> 07:36.800
Liston is going to win this fight.

07:36.800 --> 07:39.800
Clay is very young.

07:39.800 --> 07:44.800
Liston is going to kill him.

07:44.800 --> 07:47.800
Only three newspapers said,

07:47.800 --> 07:53.800
maybe Clay can beat the champion.

07:53.800 --> 07:58.800
The fight was in Miami and it was on television

07:58.800 --> 08:02.800
in a lot of American theaters too.

08:02.800 --> 08:08.800
Young Cassius Clay wanted to be famous and make a lot of money.

08:08.800 --> 08:13.800
Before his fights, he played a game.

08:13.800 --> 08:17.800
He talked and talked.

08:17.800 --> 08:26.800
Usually boxers were quiet men, but Clay's mouth was always open.

08:26.800 --> 08:32.800
Before every fight, he said to the people and the newspapers,

08:32.800 --> 08:35.800
I'm beautiful.

08:35.800 --> 08:37.800
I'm good.

08:37.800 --> 08:40.800
I'm quick and strong.

08:40.800 --> 08:49.800
I'm going to beat that man in two or three or four rounds.

08:49.800 --> 08:52.800
White people were angry with him.

08:52.800 --> 08:57.800
They didn't like this young black man with the big mouth.

08:57.800 --> 09:00.800
Kill him!

09:00.800 --> 09:03.800
They said to his opponents,

09:03.800 --> 09:08.800
Close that big mouth for him.

09:08.800 --> 09:15.800
But then, of course, a lot of people wanted to see the fight.

09:15.800 --> 09:18.800
Before the fight with Sonny Liston,

09:18.800 --> 09:21.800
Clay played this same game.

09:21.800 --> 09:29.800
Liston was very strong, but he wasn't very quick.

09:29.800 --> 09:33.800
The fight is on February 25th.

09:33.800 --> 09:38.800
In round one, Clay starts to dance.

09:38.800 --> 09:41.800
Liston can't hit him.

09:41.800 --> 09:46.800
Sometimes Clay hits his opponent's face.

09:46.800 --> 09:50.800
One, two, very quick punches.

09:50.800 --> 09:54.800
Then, he moves away.

09:54.800 --> 09:59.800
Liston goes after him, but slowly.

09:59.800 --> 10:07.800
He is big and strong, but he can't hit the young Clay.

10:07.800 --> 10:11.800
Clay goes back to his chair.

10:11.800 --> 10:16.800
He smiles at his friend, Angelo Dundee.

10:16.800 --> 10:22.800
That's the first round, and he didn't kill me, he says.

10:22.800 --> 10:25.800
I can win this.

10:25.800 --> 10:28.800
Liston is on his feet.

10:28.800 --> 10:32.800
He doesn't want to sit down.

10:32.800 --> 10:36.800
He wants to start round two.

10:36.800 --> 10:43.800
But it is the same story in rounds two and three and four.

10:44.800 --> 10:51.800
Clay dances across the ring, and Liston can't catch him.

10:51.800 --> 10:59.800
Sometimes he hits Clay, of course, but Clay is always moving away,

10:59.800 --> 11:06.800
and he is hitting Liston's face and eyes all the time.

11:06.800 --> 11:11.800
After six rounds, Liston sits down.

11:11.800 --> 11:16.800
His face is red, and one eye is closing.

11:16.800 --> 11:20.800
Suddenly, he is very tired.

11:20.800 --> 11:26.800
That man can hit, he says.

11:26.800 --> 11:32.800
Now it is round seven, and Clay is standing up on his feet.

11:32.800 --> 11:38.800
He is waiting, but his opponent isn't moving from his chair.

11:39.800 --> 11:49.800
Cassius Clay is the new champion of the world, and he is only 22 years old.

11:49.800 --> 11:53.800
He calls to the newspaper man near the ring.

11:53.800 --> 11:56.800
I am the champion.

11:56.800 --> 11:58.800
I'm beautiful.

11:58.800 --> 12:07.800
I'm number one in the world, and you were all wrong, wrong, wrong.

12:09.800 --> 12:15.800
A new name and new problems.

12:15.800 --> 12:23.800
The day after that first fight with Liston, Cassius Clay had a new name.

12:23.800 --> 12:29.800
My name is not Cassius Clay now, he said.

12:29.800 --> 12:34.800
It's Muhammad Ali.

12:35.800 --> 12:39.800
Ali's family was unhappy about this.

12:39.800 --> 12:47.800
His father, Cassius Clay, and his mother were good Christian people.

12:47.800 --> 12:53.800
Their two sons were always good Christians too.

12:53.800 --> 12:59.800
They loved their mother and father and had a happy home.

12:59.800 --> 13:03.800
What's wrong with the name Clay?

13:03.800 --> 13:06.800
His father asked.

13:06.800 --> 13:08.800
It's a good name.

13:08.800 --> 13:11.800
It's our name.

13:11.800 --> 13:17.800
Clay is a white man's name, Ali said.

13:17.800 --> 13:24.800
We have that name because our family worked for Mr. Clay, a white man.

13:24.800 --> 13:31.800
Our family came from Africa, and I would like a new name, a black name.

13:31.800 --> 13:40.800
And from today I'm going to be a Muslim because in the US white people are Christians.

13:40.800 --> 13:48.800
My black brothers are Muslims, and I'm going to be a Muslim too.

13:48.800 --> 13:54.800
Later that year Ali visited Egypt and Africa.

13:54.800 --> 13:58.800
He talked to Muslims there.

13:58.800 --> 14:02.800
There are Muslims of all colors in the world.

14:02.800 --> 14:06.800
He said, I know that now.

14:06.800 --> 14:12.800
Our problem in the US is only with the bad white people there.

14:12.800 --> 14:19.800
But he liked his new Muslim name, and he stayed a Muslim.

14:19.800 --> 14:25.800
15 months later he and Sonny Liston fought again.

14:25.800 --> 14:33.800
This time Liston was on his face on the floor in the first round.

14:33.800 --> 14:40.800
Muhammad Ali was the world boxing champion.

14:40.800 --> 14:47.800
In 1967 the US army was in Vietnam.

14:47.800 --> 14:54.800
Thousands of young Americans, white and black, went into the US army

14:54.800 --> 14:58.800
and fought the Viet Cong.

14:58.800 --> 15:03.800
The US government called Muhammad Ali and said,

15:03.800 --> 15:07.800
Your country wants you in the army.

15:07.800 --> 15:11.800
You have to go to Vietnam.

15:11.800 --> 15:14.800
Ali answered.

15:14.800 --> 15:18.800
I'm a Muslim, and Muslims want peace.

15:18.800 --> 15:21.800
They don't fat and kill people.

15:21.800 --> 15:23.800
Who are the Viet Cong?

15:23.800 --> 15:28.800
They don't want to kill me, and I don't want to kill them.

15:28.800 --> 15:33.800
I'm not going to go into the army.

15:33.800 --> 15:36.800
This was a big problem.

15:36.800 --> 15:46.800
The US government said, go into the army or go to jail.

15:46.800 --> 15:50.800
The American people were angry with Ali,

15:50.800 --> 15:54.800
and they really didn't like him.

15:54.800 --> 15:58.800
You can't box in the US.

15:58.800 --> 16:03.800
You can't be world champion, the government said.

16:03.800 --> 16:09.800
And you can't go and box in other countries.

16:09.800 --> 16:14.800
But Ali didn't go into the army.

16:14.800 --> 16:18.800
I'm a boxer, he said.

16:18.800 --> 16:23.800
I fight people because that's my job.

16:23.800 --> 16:28.800
But I don't kill people.

16:28.800 --> 16:32.800
Ali didn't box for two years.

16:32.800 --> 16:38.800
He talked to students in schools and got a little money.

16:38.800 --> 16:43.800
He talked about peace in Vietnam.

16:43.800 --> 16:48.800
The fighting in Vietnam is wrong.

16:48.800 --> 16:51.800
He always said.

16:51.800 --> 16:58.800
The government didn't send him to jail, but he didn't have much money.

16:58.800 --> 17:08.800
Then, in 1970, the US government said, you can box again.

17:08.800 --> 17:18.800
But there was a new world champion now, Joe Frazier.

17:18.800 --> 17:23.800
Joe Frazier a new opponent.

17:23.800 --> 17:27.800
Joe Frazier was a good boxer.

17:27.800 --> 17:31.800
He was strong and quick.

17:31.800 --> 17:35.800
He was an Olympic champion too.

17:35.800 --> 17:42.800
He won his medal at the Olympic Games in Tokyo in 1964.

17:42.800 --> 17:50.800
Ali's first fight with him was in New York in 1971.

17:50.800 --> 17:56.800
But two years away from boxing is a long time.

17:56.800 --> 18:00.800
The fight was very difficult for Ali.

18:00.800 --> 18:06.800
He danced, but he was slow and tired.

18:06.800 --> 18:15.800
He fought well, but after 15 long rounds, Frazier won.

18:15.800 --> 18:19.800
But Ali didn't stop fighting.

18:19.800 --> 18:28.800
After 13 fights and 12 wins, he fought Joe Frazier again in New York

18:28.800 --> 18:32.800
in 1974.

18:32.800 --> 18:38.800
Frazier fought well, but after a long and difficult fight,

18:38.800 --> 18:44.800
this time Ali was the winner.

18:44.800 --> 18:49.800
But Ali wasn't the world champion after that fight.

18:49.800 --> 18:56.800
At that time, there was a new world champion, George Foreman.

18:56.800 --> 19:01.800
I want to be world champion again.

19:01.800 --> 19:08.800
Ali said, and only George Foreman can stop me now.

19:08.800 --> 19:15.800
When and where can I fight him?

19:15.800 --> 19:21.800
Ali and Foreman, the big fight.

19:21.800 --> 19:26.800
The Ali Foreman fight wasn't in the U.S.

19:26.800 --> 19:31.800
It was in Kinshasa in Zaire.

19:31.800 --> 19:35.800
Ali loved Africa.

19:35.800 --> 19:39.800
Zaire was a black country.

19:39.800 --> 19:43.800
The government was black.

19:43.800 --> 19:50.800
Ali stayed in a beautiful big hotel, and the people there loved him.

19:51.800 --> 19:56.800
He was on the streets of Kinshasa every day,

19:56.800 --> 19:59.800
and people called to him.

19:59.800 --> 20:07.800
Ali, Bama-yeh, Ali, Bama-yeh.

20:07.800 --> 20:12.800
Bama-yeh, what are they saying?

20:12.800 --> 20:15.800
Ali asked a man.

20:15.800 --> 20:18.800
The man had a big smile.

20:19.800 --> 20:24.800
They're saying Ali kill him.

20:24.800 --> 20:30.800
Of course, George Foreman was a black American too.

20:30.800 --> 20:37.800
But Africans loved Ali because he wanted peace in Vietnam,

20:37.800 --> 20:45.800
and he was very famous because he didn't go into the U.S. Army.

20:45.800 --> 20:51.800
But George Foreman was a very big, strong boxer.

20:51.800 --> 20:58.800
He was 25 years old, and Ali was 32.

20:58.800 --> 21:03.800
And Foreman wasn't slow and heavy.

21:03.800 --> 21:10.800
At 4 o'clock, on the morning of October 30, 1974,

21:10.800 --> 21:16.800
Ali and Foreman start the big fight.

21:16.800 --> 21:20.800
It is very hot in Kinshasa.

21:20.800 --> 21:25.800
There is going to be heavy rain later in the day.

21:25.800 --> 21:32.800
In round one, Ali starts to move and dance across the ring.

21:32.800 --> 21:36.800
Foreman comes after him.

21:36.800 --> 21:41.800
In the first round, there is no winner.

21:41.800 --> 21:45.800
Ali sits down.

21:45.800 --> 21:50.800
I can't dance for 15 rounds, he thinks.

21:50.800 --> 21:55.800
It's very hot, and Foreman is quick.

21:55.800 --> 22:00.800
The old game isn't going to work.

22:00.800 --> 22:05.800
In round two, Ali stops dancing.

22:05.800 --> 22:09.800
He tries a new game.

22:09.800 --> 22:13.800
He is going to make his opponent tired.

22:13.800 --> 22:16.800
He moves slowly.

22:16.800 --> 22:20.800
Sometimes, he only stands there.

22:20.800 --> 22:25.800
Foreman hits him with big, heavy punches.

22:25.800 --> 22:28.800
People call out.

22:28.800 --> 22:30.800
Dance Ali!

22:30.800 --> 22:32.800
Dance!

22:32.800 --> 22:34.800
Don't stop moving!

22:34.800 --> 22:38.800
He's killing you!

22:38.800 --> 22:46.800
For six rounds, Foreman hits Ali again and again.

22:46.800 --> 22:50.800
But Ali stays on his feet.

22:50.800 --> 22:56.800
In round eight, Foreman is getting slow.

22:56.800 --> 23:00.800
He is very hot and tired.

23:00.800 --> 23:04.800
His hands are heavy and slow.

23:04.800 --> 23:11.800
Suddenly, Ali is quick and strong again.

23:11.800 --> 23:16.800
He hits his opponent again and again.

23:16.800 --> 23:20.800
And suddenly, Foreman is on the floor.

23:20.800 --> 23:23.800
He can't stand up.

23:23.800 --> 23:27.800
Ali is dancing.

23:27.800 --> 23:33.800
He is the world champion again.

23:33.800 --> 23:38.800
Ali stayed the champion for six years.

23:38.800 --> 23:49.800
He beat Joe Frazier again in Manila in 1975 after a long and difficult fight.

23:49.800 --> 23:57.800
In 1978, Ali lost a fight with Leon Spinks in Las Vegas.

23:57.800 --> 24:03.800
But then, seven months later, he beat him.

24:03.800 --> 24:13.800
Ali was the new world champion three times in fourteen years.

24:13.800 --> 24:18.800
A quiet time with his family.

24:18.800 --> 24:24.800
In 1980, Ali lost a fight with Larry Holmes.

24:24.800 --> 24:30.800
And in 1981, he lost again to Trevor Burbeck.

24:30.800 --> 24:34.800
He was slow and tired.

24:34.800 --> 24:40.800
He wasn't well and he went to a doctor.

24:40.800 --> 24:45.800
You're very sick, the doctor said.

24:45.800 --> 24:49.800
And you're not going to get well.

24:49.800 --> 24:58.800
It's not going to kill you, but you're going to get tired very quickly every day.

24:58.800 --> 25:04.800
You're going to walk slowly and talk slowly.

25:04.800 --> 25:09.800
I'm sorry, but we can't stop it.

25:09.800 --> 25:16.800
And, of course, you can't box.

25:16.800 --> 25:20.800
Ali stopped boxing.

25:20.800 --> 25:29.800
Now he lives quietly with his family in a big house in the country in Michigan.

25:29.800 --> 25:36.800
In the U.S. today, there are no places for whites only.

25:36.800 --> 25:43.800
In television and in movies, there are faces of all colors.

25:43.800 --> 25:47.800
People are people.

25:47.800 --> 25:56.800
Ali is happy because he was one of the first famous black Americans.

25:56.800 --> 26:02.800
And now Ali is working for peace in the world.

26:02.800 --> 26:06.800
He makes money with his famous name.

26:06.800 --> 26:12.800
He meets and talks with governments and other famous people.

26:12.800 --> 26:16.800
He gets medals these days, too.

26:16.800 --> 26:31.800
He is a worker for peace in the world, peace for all people, blacks and whites, Christians and Muslims.

26:31.800 --> 26:37.800
In the U.S. they now say Ali was right.

26:37.800 --> 26:42.800
We were wrong about Vietnam.

26:42.800 --> 26:47.800
He fought for his people and for peace.

26:47.800 --> 26:53.800
He is our American Nelson Mandela.

26:53.800 --> 26:57.800
Ali gives a lot of money to the children of the world.

26:57.800 --> 27:00.800
He loves children.

27:00.800 --> 27:04.800
He always loves children.

27:04.800 --> 27:09.800
There are nine children in his family.

27:09.800 --> 27:13.800
He moves very slowly now.

27:13.800 --> 27:15.800
He sits at home.

27:15.800 --> 27:20.800
He gets tired very quickly.

27:20.800 --> 27:25.800
He likes watching his old fights on television.

27:25.800 --> 27:31.800
He is a good Muslim and a good man.

27:31.800 --> 27:36.800
People visit him and talk with him.

27:36.800 --> 27:42.800
Young Muhammad Ali talked and worked for black Americans.

27:42.800 --> 27:46.800
Then he was a famous boxing champion.

27:46.800 --> 27:52.800
But today they call him a people's champion.

